  "datePublished": "2026-01-01",
  "description": "A distribution describes the complete pattern of how a random variable\u0026rsquo;s values are spread out — which values are possible and how probable each one is. It is the full picture of uncertainty about a quantity, rather than a single summary like the mean or median. Two datasets can have the same mean and very different distributions: the scores {50, 50, 50} and {0, 50, 100} both average to 50, but the distributions tell completely different stories about what to expect.\n",
